{"add":{"doc":{"id":"a89e43c0075661820947eea3322b1066499c071cf107936f6a2e5ea52cab6e12","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/Ada_Ciganlija_6.JPG/220px-Ada_Ciganlija_6.JPG","previous":["Ada Ciganlija is a former island on the Sava River, and Belgrade's biggest sports and recreational complex. Today it is connected with the right bank of the Sava via two causeways, creating an artificial lake. It is the most popular destination for Belgraders during the city's hot summers. There are 7 kilometres (4 miles) of long beaches and sports facilities for various sports including golf, football, basketball, volleyball, rugby union, baseball, and tennis.[166] During summer there are between 200,000 and 300,000 bathers daily.[167]"],"after":["Extreme sports are available, such as bungee jumping, water skiing, and paintballing.[166][168] There are numerous tracks on the island, where it is possible to ride a bike, go for a walk, or go jogging.[166][168] Apart from Ada, Belgrade has total of 16 islands[169] on the rivers, many still unused. Among them, the Great War Island, at the confluence of Sava, stands out as an oasis of unshattered wildlife (especially birds).[170] These areas, along with nearby Small War Island, are protected by the city's government as a nature preserve.[171]"]}}}